Here is the first method for overlaying shape data on a raster.

Use the following packages (install them first), then use them via the library() call: tmap, tmaptools, rgdal, sp, OpenStreetMap, osmdata

These calls are useful: readOGR(), tmaptools::read_osm(), tm_shape(), tm_raster(), tm_dots()

  1. readOGR() your shapefile, store it in a var
  2. read_osm() the bbox of #1 above, store it in a var
  3. do tm_shape() on #2 + tm_raster() + tm_shape() on #1 + tm_dots() to specify point color and size
library(rgdal)
ogr <- readOGR(dsn = "mygeodata/placemarks.shp")
OGR data source with driver: ESRI Shapefile 
Source: "D:\USC\USC Course\CSCI 585\HW\5 R\mygeodata\placemarks.shp", layer: "placemarks"
with 13 features
It has 11 fields
osm <- read_osm(ogr)
tm_shape(osm) + tm_raster() + tm_shape(ogr) + tm_dots(size = 1, col='red')

And heres the second.

Use these packages: PBSmapping, ggmap And these calls: importShapefile(), as.data.frame(), get_map(), ggmap(), geom_point()

  1. importShapefile() into a var
  2. convert it (#1 above) to a dataframe, store it in a var
  3. get_map() with a location thats in your collection of (lat,long), store it in a var
  4. do ggmap() on #3, + geom_point() on #2
library(ggmap)
file<-importShapefile("mygeodata/placemarks")
df <- data.frame(file)
map<-get_map(location = c(df['X'][1,],df['Y'][1,]),zoom = 15)
Map from URL : http://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/staticmap?center=34.028557,-118.284303&zoom=15&size=640x640&scale=2&maptype=terrain&language=en-EN&sensor=false
ggmap(map) + geom_point(data=df, aes(x=X, y=Y), color='red')
